Hello,

Because it's not possible to start a cron every second, I wrote something very simple that should makes my e-mails being sent faster:

``` php
use Symfony\Bundle\SwiftmailerBundle\Command\SendEmailCommand as OriginalSendEmailCommand;

class SendEmailCommand extends OriginalSendEmailCommand
{
    /**
     * @see Command
     */
    protected function configure()
    {
        parent::configure();
        $this
            ->setName('xxx:spool:send')
            ->setDescription('Sends emails from the spool repeatedly')
            ->addOption('waiting-time', null, InputOption::VALUE_OPTIONAL, 'Time to wait between two calls', 1000)
        ;
    }
    /**
     * {@inheritdoc}
     */
    protected function execute(InputInterface $input, OutputInterface $output)
    {
        while (true) {
            parent::execute($input, $output);
            usleep($input->getOption('waiting-time') * 1000);
        }
    }
}
```

This is just starting the swiftmailer:spool:send command each `waiting-time`. Here is the crontab that ensure this infinite loop is running:

```
* * * * * /sbin/start-stop-daemon --start --make-pidfile --pidfile /opt/xxx/run/worker01_mail.pid --chuid worker --oknodo --exec /usr/bin/php -- /opt/xxx/app/console xxx:spool:send --env=cli --no-debug > /dev/null
```

But this is having a strange behavior for a few e-mails. Sometimes an e-mail is stuck in the spool in the .sending state. Does this command make sense to you? Am I missing something? Like a __destruct() method that is no longer called with that kind of command, and could maybe change the wanted behavior?

Thanks for your halp, and thanks for the great tool :)

