After calling addPart() in the class \Swift_Message, it's no longer possible to access the content type passed to the constructor.

```
$message = new Swift_Message('foo', 'html body', 'text/html');

echo $message->getContentType(); // output: "text/html"

$message->addPart('text body', 'text/plain');

echo $message->getContentType(); // output: "multipart/alternative"
```

This causes problems when implementing a transport for an API which composites multi-part emails itself, such as Mandrill.

As you can see in the example below, Mandrill expects the html and text body in API calls to be added to separate fields.

```
{
    "subject": "foo",
    "to": [
        {
            "email": "to@example.com",
            "type": "to"
        }
    ],
    "from_email": "from@example.com",
    "html": "html body",
    "text": "text body"
}
```

To determine if $message->getBody() should go into the "html" or "text" field, I need to check $message->getContentType(). Because getContentType() now returns "multipart/alternative", I'm unable to do this.

As a result, I have to resort to the following nasty hack.

```
$messageRef = new \ReflectionClass($message);
if($messageRef->hasProperty('_userContentType')){
    $propRef = $messageRef->getProperty('_userContentType');
    $propRef->setAccessible(true);
    $contentType = $propRef->getValue($message);
}
```

Would it be possible to add a method to \Swift_Message to expose the content type passed to the constructor?

